<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900628-0047</DOCNO><DOCID>900628-0047.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- E-Systems Inc.:   Electronics Firm Receives   Contract for System Test</HL><DATE>06/28/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   ESY MOB</CO><LP>   E-Systems, Inc., Dallas, said it has received a&quot;multimillion-dollar&quot; contract from a Mobil Corp. unit totest its computer-based mass storage system over a three-yearperiod.   The contract represents the first adaptation of the datastorage system for a nongovernment group, said Philip J.Rasch, manager of business development for the project.E-Systems, an electronic systems and products company, hopesthe contract with Mobil will give it a leg up on an estimated$2 billion market in the 1990s.</LP><TEXT>   The mass storage system will store the oil company'sexploration data on tape cartridges similar to those used byvideo cassette recorders. The recording system was adaptedfrom one produced by Ampex Corp., Redwood City, Calif., forbroadcast television. The cassettes are stored on shelves andretrieved by robot for playback on a recorder; the system isoperated by a minisupercomputer produced by Convex ComputerCorp., Richardson, Texas.   Ampex has the rights to market its portion of the system,primarily the recording device, for non-automated uses.</TEXT></DOC>